ef name=\"bb19980620\">{{cite web|first=Anita|last=Samuels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-w0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=MONICA+%22THE+BOY+IS+MINE%22&hl=de&ei=pOPkTc-YEo3LtAavmJmHBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=MONICA%20%22THE%20BOY%20IS%20MINE%22&f=false|title=Sharing A Hit Duet, Arista's Monica Finds Her Own Voice On 'Boy'|accessdate=2011-05-31|date=1998-06-20|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n||May 5, 1998\n||[[Rhythmic contemporary|Radio]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|United States<ref name=\"bb19980620\"/>\n||May 19, 1998\n||[[CD single]]\n|}\n\n== Cover versions and remixes==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Amber Riley by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| width1 = 170\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Naya Rivera by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| width2 = 170\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Riley as ''Mercedes'' (left) and Rivera as ''Santana'' (right) recorded a cover version of the song.\n}}\n*In 1998, [[UK garage]] group [[Architechs]] remixed \"The Boy Is Mine\", and released it as a [[white label]] bootleg which eventually sold 20,000 copies. This remix became highly popular due to incessant airplay on pirate radio.<ref>{{cite web|author=Simon Reynolds |url=http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/magazine/simon-reynolds-ukg-rb |title=Simon Reynolds\u2019s Video Countdown: UKG x R&B |publisher=Red Bull Music Academy |date= |accessdate=2014-01-16}}</ref>\n*In 2001, Brandy and Monica's vocals were merged with [[Modjo]]'s 2000 dance hit single \"[[Lady (Hear Me Tonight)]]\" by British DJs [[Stuntmasterz]]. Starting as an underground hit, \"The Ladyboy Is Mine\" was later commercially released to become a moderate hit across Europe, reaching the top ten in the United Kingdom, Belgium and the top forty in France and Switzerland. The commercial release didn't include the vocal sample from Modjo's \"Lady\" as Warner Brothers label East West were unable to clear it. Instead the release used the same sample from [[Chic (band)|Chic]]'s \"[[Soup for One (song)|Soup for One]]\" and created an alternate version that only featured Brandy and Monica.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Stuntmasterz&titel=The+Lady+Boy+Is+Mine&cat=s|title=Stuntmasterz\u2013 The Lady Boy Is Mine swisscharts.com|publisher=[[Swiss Singles Chart]]. Hung Medien|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref>\n*A remixed version of the song by pop singers [[Tynisha Keli]], an American working in Japan, and [[Beni (singer)|Beni]], a Japanese singer, was released in 2009.\n*The song was covered by [[Naya Rivera]] and [[Amber Riley]] for the TV show ''Glee'' as their respective characters.\n*In 2015, French girl band When We Were Young released a version in their language featuring French rapper [[Dry (rapper)|Dry]].<ref>[http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=When+We+Were+Young&titel=The+Boy+Is+Mine&cat=s Les Charts: When We Were Young - \"The Boy Is Mine\" page]</ref>\n*The same year, \"The Boy Is Mine\" was sampled on \"[[The Girl Is Mine (99 Souls song)|The Girl Is Mine]]\" by British music duo [[99 Souls]].\n*In 2016, the song was covered by producer J2 and featured StarGzrLily and Anjolee the Free. It was used in the trailers for the 2016 US film ''[[When the Bough Breaks (2016 film)|When the Bough Breaks]]'', starring [[Morris Chestnut]] and [[Regina Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1-TixDPOS9M|title=WHEN THE BOUGH BREAKS TRAILER SONG 'The Boy Is Mine' J2 Feat StarGzrLily & Anjolee The Free|first=|last=J2 Producer|date=16 August 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n*On the October 14, 2019, episode of reality television singing competition show ''[[The Voice (American season 17)|The Voice]]'', Team [[John Legend|(John) Legend]] members Khalea Lynee of [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], and Zoe Upkins of [[Nashville, Tennessee]], performed the song in a Battle round.  Coaches [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Gwen Stefani]], and [[Blake Shelton]] were all divided, with Stefani preferring Upkins's performance, Shelton preferring Lynee's performance, and Clarkson abstaining from naming her preference.  Legend chose to agree with Shelton and named Lynee the winner of the Battle, advancing her to the Knockout rounds.  Soon after, Legend also attempted to save Upkins and keep her on his team, as well, although Clarkson and Stefani both attempted to steal her instead, with the three coaches' attempts saving her from elimination regardless of her choice.  Ultimately, Upkins opted to remain on Team Legend, advancing to the Knockouts on his team.\n\n===Charts (Glee Cast version)===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2010)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|76\n|-\n| [[UK Singles Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|62\n|-\n| [[Irish Singles Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|46\n|-\n| [[Canadian Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|60\n|-\n|[[ARIA Charts]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|90\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones]]\n*[[List of Hot 100 number-one singles of 1998 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mtv.com/videos/brandy-monica/747265/the-boy-is-mine.jhtml \"The Boy Is Mine\" music video] on MTV.com\n\n{{Brandy Norwood singles}}\n{{Monica songs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boy Is Mine, The}}\n[[Category:1998 singles]]\n[[Category:1998 songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Brandy Norwood songs]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Single Top 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Monica (singer) songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Joseph Kahn]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one dance singles in Canada]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Dallas Austin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rodney Jerkins]]\n[[Category:Vocal duets]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Rodney Jerkins]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Fred Jerkins III]]\n[[Category:Songs written by LaShawn Daniels]]\n[[Category:Answer songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about infidelity]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Brandy Norwood]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1998 duet single by Brandy and Monica}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Boy Is Mine\n| cover      = The Boy Is Mine (Brandy single) coverart.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]] and [[Monica (singer)|Monica]]\n| album      = [[Never Say Never (Brandy album)|Never Say Never]]'' and ''[[The Boy Is Mine (album)|The Boy Is Mine]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1998|5|19|mf=y}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Cassette single|Cassette]]|[[12-inch single|12-inch]]|[[CD single|CD]]}}\n| recorded   = {{unbulleted list|October{{snd}}December 1997|{{small|(Los Angeles, California}}|{{small|and Atlanta, Georgia)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1426545/brandy-back-studio.jhtml |title=Brandy Back In The Studio - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV.com |date=1997-10-10 |accessdate=2014-01-16}}</ref>}}\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = {{unbulleted list|4:54 {{small|(album version)}}|4:03 {{small|(radio version)}}}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[LaShawn Daniels]]|[[Rodney Jerkins]]|[[Fred Jerkins III]]|Japhe Tejeda|[[Brandy Norwood]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Darkchild|Brandy|[[Dallas Austin]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Missing You (Brandy, Gladys Knight, Tamia, and Chaka Khan song)|Missing You]]\n | prev_year  = 1996\n | title      = The Boy Is Mine\n | year       = 1998\n | next_title = [[Top of the World (Brandy song)|Top of the World]]\n | next_year  = 1998\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Monica (singer)|Monica]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[For You I Will (Monica song)|For You I Will]]\n | prev_year  = 1997\n | title      = The Boy Is Mine\n | year       = 1998\n | next_title = [[The First Night]]\n | next_year  = 1998\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''The Boy Is Mine'''\" is a 1998 [[duet]] by American singers [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]] and [[Monica (singer)|Monica]] written and composed by [[LaShawn Daniels]], Japhe Tejeda, [[Fred Jerkins III]], [[Rodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins]], and Brandy with coproduction by Darkchild and [[Dallas Austin]]. It was released as the [[lead single]] from both singers' second albums from 1998, ''[[Never Say Never (Brandy album)|Never Say Never]]'' by Brandy and ''[[The Boy Is Mine (album)|The Boy Is Mine]]'' by Monica. Inspired by [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Paul McCartney]]'s 1982 duet \"[[The Girl Is Mine]]\", the lyrics of the [[mid-tempo]] [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] track revolve around two women fighting over a man.<ref name=HeraldS>{{cite web|title=We Assess The Best, and Worst, All-Time Musical Duets |last=Adams |first=Cameron |date=2008-06-19 |work=Herald Sun |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,23888090-2902,00.html |accessdate=2008-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622151152/http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0%2C21985%2C23888090-2902%2C00.html |archivedate=June 22, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe song received generally positive reviews from music critics and was the first [[Number one hit|number-one pop hit]] for both artists, in the US and internationally. Exploiting the media's presumption of a rivalry between the two young singers,<ref name=\"sixty-one\">{{cite web|title=At Age 21, The N.J.-based Producer Is King of His World|author=Farber, Jim|date=2002-02-06|work=NY Daily News|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/b-rodney-age-21-n-based-producer-king-world-article-1.872611|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref> \"The Boy Is Mine\" became the best-selling song of the year in the US, selling 2.6 million copies, and spent 13 weeks at the top of the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] during the summer of 1998. It became the second song in the history of the chart to ascend directly to number-one from a previous position beneath the Top 20, at number 23, following [[The Beatles]] and the 27\u20131 leap of their single \"[[Can't Buy Me Love]]\" in April 1964. Internationally, the single also achieved a strong charting, peaking at number one in [[Canada]], the [[Netherlands]] and [[New Zealand]], while reaching the top five on most of the other charts on which it appeared.<ref name=\"sixty-one\"/>\n\n\"The Boy Is Mine\" was awarded the [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group]] and received nominations for both [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]] in 1999. At the [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Award]]s, the song won in three categories, including Hot 100 Sales Single of Year. In 2008, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' listed it 54th on its 50th Anniversary All-Time Hot 100 Top Songs chart, and 18th on the All-Time Top R&B/Hip-Hop Songs countdown.<ref name=\"SweetSoulMusic\">{{cite web|title=Sweet Soul Music: Top Billboard Hot 100 R&B/Hip-Hop Songs |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=Billboard.com |url=https://www.billboard.com/specials/hot100/charts/top-rbhiphop.shtml |accessdate=2012-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131040254/http://www.billboard.com/specials/hot100/charts/top-rbhiphop.shtml |archivedate=January 31, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[music video]] for the single, directed by [[Joseph Kahn]], starred the singers and [[Mekhi Phifer]]. It was nominated for two [[MTV Video Music Award]]s, including [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best R&B Video|Best R&B Video]]. In 2012, after 14 years, the singers reunited on the single \"[[It All Belongs to Me]]\".\n\n==Background and composition==\n[[File:The Boy Is Mine sample.ogg|thumb|right|A sample from the song's chorus, featuring both singer's vocals.]]\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Michael Jackson 1984.jpg\n| width1 = 123\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Paul McCartney black and white 2010.jpg\n| width2 = 133\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = The song was partially inspired by \"[[The Girl Is Mine]]\", a 1982 duet by [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Paul McCartney]] from the former's ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]'' (1982).\n}} \n\"The Boy Is Mine\" was a song Brandy wrote with [[Rodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins]], his brother [[Fred Jerkins III]], Japhe Tejeda, and [[LaShawn Daniels]]. The singer came up with its concept while watching an episode of ''[[The Jerry Springer Show]]'' [[tabloid talk show]], where [[love triangle]]s among the guests was the theme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1999-01-12/news/9901110643_1_abc-entertainment-tim-allen-jerry-springer-show|title=Everybody Know What Time It Is? The End?|first=Hal|last=Boedecker|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=1999-01-12|accessdate=2001-05-31}}</ref> Created as a solo track, Brandy originally recorded the song alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soultracks.com/brandy.htm?|first1=David|last1=Nathan|first2=Chris|last2=Rizik|title=''The Best of Brandy''|publisher=Soultracks.com|date=1999-01-12|accessdate=2011-05-31}}</ref> After listening to the result, however, she and Jerkins thought it would work better as a duet,<ref name=\"la1\">{{cite web|first=Elysa|last=Gardner|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1998/jul/07/entertainment/ca-1304|title=Next From the Diva Machine|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=1998-07-07|accessdate=2012-02-24}}</ref> an idea which was further inspired by [[Paul McCartney]] and [[Michael Jackson]]'s 1982 hit duet \"[[The Girl Is Mine]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/1998-07-14/entertainment/18081346_1_miss-thang-clive-davis-rumor|title=Monica's Growing Success Teen Singer Has A 'Boy' Wonder Of A Hit - And A New Maturity?|first=Karen|last=Hunter|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=1998-07-04|accessdate=2011-05-31}}</ref> At Brandy's request, her label [[Atlantic Records]] approached fellow R&B teen singer [[Monica (singer)|Monica]] to collaborate:<ref name=\"msn1\"/> The pair had seen each other in passing at award shows and other live events, and Brandy thought a duet would help combat ongoing rumors that the singers were rivals.<ref name=\"la1\"/> With the permission of [[Clive Davis]], who headed Monica's record company [[Arista Records]], Monica eventually signed on to the project.<ref name=\"msn1\">{{cite web|first=Rebecca|last=Silverstein|url=http://wonderwall.msn.com/music/brandy-and-monica-dish-on-their-musical-reunion-1666299.story|title=Brandy and Monica Dish on Their Musical Reunion|work=[[MSN]].com|date=2012-02-10|accessdate=2012-02-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214044742/http://wonderwall.msn.com/music/brandy-and-monica-dish-on-their-musical-reunion-1666299.story|archivedate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n\nThe song has a [[tempo]] of 93 beats per minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://songbpm.com/brandy/the+boy+is+mine|title=BPM for 'the boy is mine' by brandy {{!}} songbpm.com|website=songbpm.com|access-date=2016-06-11}}</ref> Written in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[C-sharp minor|C{{sharp}} minor]], it follows a [[chord progression]] of F{{sharp}}m<small>9</small>\u2013C{{sharp}}m<small>9</small>, and the vocals span from G{{sharp}}<sub>3</sub> to F{{sharp}}<sub>4</sub>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0084444|title=Brandy \"The Boy Is Mine\" Sheet Music in C# Minor (transposable) - Download & Print|last=Daniels|first=LaShawn|website=Musicnotes.com|access-date=2016-06-11}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the two artists recorded their vocals for the song together with Jerkins and his production team at the [[Ocean Way Recording|Record One Studios]] in [[North Hollywood]]. However, the joint recording was felt to be a failure so Monica re-recorded her vocals separately at the DARP Studios in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] with longtime contributor [[Dallas Austin]] and turned the song into a more mature pop sound.<ref name=\"la1\"/> (Thus, Austin would later share the main production credit alongside Jerkins.<ref name=\"liner notes\"/>) Though both Brandy and Monica repeatedly denied the song reflected any actual rivalry between them, tabloids began writing the opposite. There were claims that Monica was upset when Brandy performed the song solo on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'', and Brandy was reportedly miffed when Monica opted to take the name of the duet for the title of her [[The Boy Is Mine (album)|second album]]. Following reports that the pair came to blows during a rehearsal for a performance at the [[1998 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Awards]] in September 1998, talk of the rivalry became so loud that the singers' managers released a joint statement in which they called the press out for its \"disturbing behavior\" and called the \"ongoing negativity [as] totally unfair.\"<ref name=\"yahoo1\">{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/monica/news/brandy-and-monica-held-hands-and-prayed-together--12032969 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130209221059/http://music.yahoo.com/monica/news/brandy-and-monica-held-hands-and-prayed-together--12032969 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-02-09 |title=Brandy And Monica 'Held Hands And Prayed Together' |work=[[Yahoo! Music]] |date=1998-09-16 |accessdate=2012-02-26 }}</ref> As with \"The Boy Is Mine,\" Jerkins later claimed that both singers \"didn\u2019t get along\" during production and that he and Dexter Simmons remixed the track seven times to keep everything even.<ref name=\"bb-duets\"/> In a 2012 interview with [[WZMX]], Monica spoke about her past relationship with Brandy:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"We were young. We could barely stay in the room with each other. By no means was it jealousy or envy. She and I are polar opposites and instead of embracing that, we used our differences as reasons not to be amongst each other.\"<ref name=\"wzmx\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2Zf7OJuLbcY|title=Monica explains why she used to hate Brandy & talks about upcoming tour with Brandy|work=[[WZMX]]|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=2012-02-21|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Chart performance ===\nOn June 6, 1998, \"The Boy Is Mine\" became both singers' first number-one hit and fifth top ten entry for each on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"bb06061998\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bw4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA102&dq=%22the+boy+is+mine%22+brandy&hl=de&ei=C6DkTZ3uNoXFswbRoJyQBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22the%20boy%20is%20mine%22%20brandy&f=false|title=Brandy & Monica's 'Boy' Takes A Leap|last=Bronson|first=Fred|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=1998-06-06|accessdate=2001-05-31}}</ref> Bouncing from number 23 to the top spot, it became the second song in the history of the chart to ascend directly to number-one from a previous position beneath the Top 20, following [[The Beatles]] and the 27\u20131 leap of their single \"[[Can't Buy Me Love]]\" in April 1964.<ref name=\"bb06061998\"/> In addition, it was the first number-one collaboration between solo women since 1979's two-weeks number-one run of \"[[No More Tears (Enough Is Enough)]],\" performed by [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Donna Summer]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Gary|last=Trust |title=Weekly Chart Notes: Rihanna, Katy Perry, Paul Simon|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Billboard.com|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/471928/weekly-chart-notes-rihanna-katy-perry-paul-simon|date=2011-04-21|accessdate=2012-02-24}}</ref> The same week, \"The Boy Is Mine\" also moved to number-one on the [[Hot R&B Singles]], [[Hot 100 Singles Sales]] and [[Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]] charts.<ref name=\"bb06061998\"/> Within the first month of its purchasable release the song went on to sell 605,000 units.<ref name=\"bb19980620\"/> It spent thirteen consecutive weeks atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has since been ranked among [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones|the longest running number-one songs in US chart history]], sharing this record with [[Boyz II Men]]'s \"[[End of the Road (Boyz II Men song)|End of the Road]]\" (1992). \"The Boy Is Mine\" was the best-selling single of 1998 in the US, with sales of 2,591,000, with the second best-selling single being [[Next (group)|Next]]'s \"[[Too Close (Next song)|Too Close]]\".<ref name=grein>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110512023856/http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74361/chart-watch-extra-20-years-of-top-songs/ |archivedate=May 12, 2011 |url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74361/chart-watch-extra-20-years-of-top-songs/ |title=Chart Watch Extra: 20 Years Of Top Songs |last=Grein |first=Paul |website=[[Yahoo! Music]] |date=May 6, 2011 |accessdate=June 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA75|title=1998 Was The Year For Soundtrack, Women, Boy Bands|last=Jeffrey|first=Don|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=BPI Communications Inc. |date=1999-01-30|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref> It was certified [[double platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and was ranked eighth on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Decade-End Charts.<ref name=\"1990sbb\">{{Cite book | author = Geoff Mayfield | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=RA1-PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = 1999 The Year in Music Totally '90s: Diary of a Decade - The listing of Top Pop Albums of the '90s & Hot 100 Singles of the '90s | publisher = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date = December 25, 1999 | accessdate = October 15, 2010}}</ref> The song spent 18 weeks in the top 10 and a total of 27 weeks in the Top 50.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nOutside the US, \"The Boy Is Mine\" reached the top-ten in over 14 countries and topped the chart in Canada, the Netherlands and New Zealand.  In Canada, the song debuted on the [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' Singles Chart]] at number 74 on the ''RPM'' issue dated June 1, 1998,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3577&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles - Volume 67, No. 10, June 01 1998|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=1998-06-01|accessdate=2012-02-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101174121/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3577&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=2016-01-01}}</ref> and reached the top spot of the chart on August 21, 1998.<ref name=canada>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3663&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles - Volume 67, No. 21, August 17, 1998|magazine=RPM|date=1998-08-17|accessdate=2012-02-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112170143/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3663&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=January 12, 2016}}</ref> It was present on the chart for a total of 45 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8362&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles - Volume 69, No. 16, August 09 1999|date=1999-04-09|work=RPM|accessdate=2012-02-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112170143/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8362&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=2016-01-12}}</ref> It reached the top two in Belgium, France (platinum), Ireland, Norway (gold), and the United Kingdom (platinum); the top-five in Australia, Germany (gold), Sweden, and Switzerland (gold) and the top-ten in Austria (gold) and Italy.<ref name=\"WW\">{{cite web|title=\"The Boy Is Mine\" Chart History|work=Swisscharts.com|url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Brandy+%26+Monica&titel=The+Boy+Is+Mine&cat=s|accessdate=2008-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and recognitions ===\nThe single won many awards throughout 1998 and 1999. It was nominated for three [[Grammy Awards]] at the [[41st Grammy Awards|41st annual ceremony]], winning both singers their first prize by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] in the [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals]] category. It, however, lost in its nominations for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]] to [[Celine Dion]]'s \"[[My Heart Will Go On]]\" and [[Lauryn Hill]]'s \"[[Doo Wop (That Thing)]]\" respectively. The song garnered  three [[Billboard Music Awards]]. It is listed as the 62nd on the most successful singles in France ever.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://lescharts.com/bestall.asp |title=Les charts fran\u00e7ais |publisher=lescharts.com |accessdate=2014-01-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205065748/http://lescharts.com/bestall.asp |archivedate=2014-02-05 }}{{failed verification|date=March 2015}}</ref> It is also listed among one of the most successful 200 singles in Australia, Netherlands and Belgium in music history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Brandy+%26+Monica&titel=The+Boy+Is+Mine&cat=s |title=Brandy & Monica - The Boy Is Mine |publisher=ultratop.be |date= |accessdate=2014-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIt was listed as number 55 of the Hot 100 singles of all time by ''Billboard''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GwoEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&lr=&rview=1&pg=PA32&hl=ko#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=19 September 1998|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|via=Google Books}}</ref> in 1998. This position was raised to number 54 in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Billboard Hot 100 All-Time Top Songs (60-51) |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=Billboard.com |url=https://www.billboard.com/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-60.shtml |accessdate=2012-02-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308213104/http://www.billboard.com/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-60.shtml |archivedate=March 8, 2012 }}</ref> In addition, it was listed 18th on the All-Time Top R&B/Hip-Hop Songs countdown.<ref name=\"SweetSoulMusic\"/> In 2008, ''Billboard'' ranked the song third on a special [[Billboard (magazine)|The 40 Biggest Duets of All Time]] listing.<ref name=\"bb-duets\">{{cite web|title=The 40 Biggest Duets of All Time|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Billboard.com|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/list/473075/the-40-biggest-duets-of-all-time|accessdate=2012-02-24}}</ref> The song is the best-selling song of 1998 in the United States with 2.6 million copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA75&dq=sOUNDSCAN+TOP+SELLING+ALBUMS+OF+1998&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FKw2UcrtLsSEygHEx4HwBg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=sOUNDSCAN+TOP+SELLING+ALBUMS+OF+1998&f=false|title=Billboard|date=30 January 1999|work=Billboard|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nMaking its debut on April 22, 1998,<ref>http://mvdbase.com/video.php?id=4354</ref> the official music video uses the [[radio edit]] version without the intro. The video begins with Brandy watching an episode of ''[[The Jerry Springer Show]].'' Next we see Monica who, using her remote, accidentally turns Brandy's TV along with her own to watch an old romantic movie. Confused, Brandy changes her channel back. Much to their dismay, whenever one of them turns the channel, the other's TV is also turned. They begin singing. The next scene shows the two discussing their problem among their separate groups of friends. The titular boy himself (played by [[Mekhi Phifer]]) then appears outside adjacent apartments, 6 & 7, where we later discover the two girls live; all their friends walk by him as they exit their respective friend's place. The girls are seen next arguing through their adjoining bedroom wall, until the boy phones them one after the other. They each overhear the other's conversation through the wall, realizing that they've both been played. They proceed to gather up all gifts and memorabilia related to the boy and toss them out the door. After Brandy and Monica sing more through the song's lyrics, the boy knocks on Brandy's door. The door opens showing Brandy for a brief moment before she opens the door wider to reveal Monica beside her. The boy is taken aback, and the door is slammed in his face.\n\nThe video, filmed in April 1998 and used 90-degree tilts to depict the drama and the playfulness between the two. It was nominated for two [[1998 MTV Video Music Awards]], for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best R&B Video|Best R&B Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]], but lost to both [[Wyclef Jean]]'s \"[[Gone Till November]]\" and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s \"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\" respectively.\n\n==Live performances==\nBrandy first performed the song by herself on ''[[The Tonight Show]]''. Following that, she and Monica first performed it together at the [[1998 MTV Video Music Awards]] in [[Los Angeles]] at the [[Gibson Amphitheatre]] on September 10, 1998,<ref name=\"jet10051998\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QzsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA39&dq=%22the+boy+is+mine%22+brandy&hl=de&ei=C6DkTZ3uNoXFswbRoJyQBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22the%20boy%20is%20mine%22%20brandy&f=false|title=Brandy And Monica's Managers Deny Alleged Fight Backstage At MTV's VIdeo Music Awards|work=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=1998-10-05|accessdate=2011-05-31}}</ref> an event which remains, to date, Brandy and Monica's only television broadcast performance of the song. The pair came together a second time on December 16, 2008 for a surprise performance at [[Atlanta]]\u2019s ''V103 Soul Session'', singing it [[a cappella]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/12/18/brandy-and-monica-reunite-on-stage/#more-9986|title=Brandy and Monica Reunite On Stage|work=[[Rap-Up]]|publisher=Rap-Up.com|date=2008-12-18|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, they performed the song with their new duet \"[[It All Belongs To Me]]\" at [[V-103]]'s \"Conversation/Soul Session\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/03/23/brandy-and-monica-pay-tribute-to-whitney-houston-in-atlanta/ |title=Brandy and Monica Pay Tribute to Whitney Houston in Atlanta |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2012-03-23 |accessdate=2014-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Track listings ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''US maxi CD single'''\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (album version)\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (club mix)\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (radio version; with [[introduction (music)|intro]])\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (album instrumentals)\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (a cappella)\n\n'''2-track CD single'''\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (album version)\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (instrumental)\n{{col-2}}\n'''European maxi CD / Australian CD'''\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\" (radio edit without intro) \u2013 4:00\n#\"The Boy Is Mine\"